<subSubSection id="6DB346D32171861FCA237828CCCDF042" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="857EC17BA04F9D1DC87E158ECFB7184D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0DF62E21C2786FA5246EB1C6703D2C85" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pine woodland from 1500 to 2000 m. Endemic to Oaxaca.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A8EDBE402C890A9698AA0CC0E4C28FFF" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="3594E7CD51A96FDCC42C9C392A07C780" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">MEXICO. Oaxaca</emphasis>
: Abasolo, Santa 
<taxonomicName id="D2864F8A1C956EE08F7DBCBA55DD70C5" authority="Buenavista, A. Saynes" authorityName="Buenavista, A. Saynes" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rosa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
Rosa Buenavista, 
<emphasis id="EABA78F15DBA07197203C3B1B6C5E5CE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. Saynes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
627 (IEB); San Felipe Tejalapa, 
<emphasis id="4949D40CB7EA9DB3624341E905B9D45E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. Cruz</emphasis>
133 (IEB).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D87E5A2A4629CE49F20DDA43EC519D80" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="A07FEC496F38F3BEF80A067A9D3DAD3C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="83355616164B6042C9D2CB74078E969D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Resembling 
<taxonomicName id="81A6A8DDD5032C2A76F2520B8605DB96" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="crinicalyx">
<emphasis id="E69C66F570796D1EA61AA237FC3D4B15" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea crinicalyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and allies in the fleshy spines on the calyx but the long thick pedicels are somewhat reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName id="F7675EBB690E282A95E66F3AB6465640" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="setosa">
<emphasis id="9EEB7891A17C1C21AEA9C43C2524DA23" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. setosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The solitary flowers and ovate, cordate, glabrous, spineless leaves render this species very distinct.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
